For each of the following scenarios, explain if you would use Django (and why or why not):

You need to develop a web application with multiple users.
Yes. Django already includes tools for handling users, sessions, and permissions. This makes it easier to
build a multi-user app without writing everything from scratch.

You need fast deployment and the ability to make changes as you proceed.
Yes. Django comes with many built-in features, so you can set up the main parts of your app quickly.
Its structure also makes it easy to update and add new features as you go.

You need to build a very basic application, which doesn’t require any database access or file operations.
No. Django is too heavy for a very simple app. A lighter tool like Flask or even a basic HTML page would be
easier and faster to use.

You want to build an application from scratch and want a lot of control over how it works.
No. Django expects you to follow its structure, so you have less freedom to shape everything yourself. A smaller
framework gives more flexibility if you want full control.

You’re about to start working on a big project and are afraid of getting stuck and needing additional support.
Yes. Django is a good choice for large projects because it is reliable and well-documented. Its big community also
makes it easier to find help when you need it.
